There's a lot of factors here - in no particular order:
1. First but not foremost, O'Malley is a non-factor. He may get a few delegates, but definitely no more than 3-5% of the total delegate pool. A more interesting question is where those who initially go for him end up if they don't get enough caucus goers to get a delegate. The Des Moines Register (http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/31/politics/martin-omalley-important-iowa/) says they'd split relatively evenly in the groups that have already identified a second candidate, but I suspect Clinton would ultimate come out ahead of Sanders in that O'Malley's ideology is closer to Clinton's.
2. Sanders self-identifying as a socialist is problematic. While he has experienced tremendous growth in the polls, I strongly suspect that label will be problematic for older voters and that they'll break toward Clinton.
3. The weather tomorrow will be a major factor. In the western part of the state, snow could begin as early as 6 p.m. In Des Moines and points east, it'll be later. If you look at the relative importance of counties (http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2016/01/30/iowa-democratic-caucus-counties-to-watch/), most of the State's more liberal areas (Iowa City, Dubuque, etc.) will likely wrap up PRIOR to the storm, which bodes well for Sanders. This is one of my primary reasons for departing with the FiveThirtyEight forecast, which I typically trust on polling. A two-for-one prediction here: If Sanders wins Iowa, he easily wins New Hampshire though he will need to work hard to win the subsequent states. If Clinton wins, her odds of winning NH are significantly better, and Sanders will be fighting an even harder uphill battle.

On Education/Voting Demographic:
Bernie Sanders' primary voting demographic is targeted toward young Americans struggling to access the "American Dream". He has interest in providing free access to public educational institutions by imposing higher tax rates upon those in high income brackets.
Hillary Clinton's campaign has primarily aimed to provide a more centrist, fiscally conservative approach to education reform. As an example, she has stated that she has interest in decreasing interest rates on student loans to reduce financial burden on college graduates.
The Pivot Point: 
In Fall 2013, Iowa had roughly 330,000 students attending higher education institutions. The population of Iowa is roughly 3,200,000. Therefore, we can estimate that college students, the primary demographic of Bernie Sanders' campaign, represent only about 10% of Iowa's population.  On Healthcare:
Bernie Sanders' campaign has drawn both support and criticism for its endorsement of a single-payer system (see: Canada), and an aggressive stance in favor of increased regulation of the Pharmaceutical industry.
Hillary Clinton's campaign has focused on support of the continued growth of the Affordable Care Act ("Obamacare"), with few alterations to the legislation anticipated.
The Pivot Point: Between 2010 and 2011, Iowa was the fourth state out of the top ten states to witness the highest drop in insurance competition. This is according to a 2013 report by the American Medical Association. Such a shift, possibly attributed to effects of the Affordable Care Act, may lead to increased support for Sanders' anti-industry approach to Healthcare Reform. On the other hand, one of Iowa's newly developing industries is the Biotechnology sector. Supporters of the newly developed industry may find Clinton's stance more favorable. On General Economy:
Pivot Point: The state of Iowa currently has nine income brackets, with taxes ranging from 0.36 - 8.98%. The state's median household income is around $48,000. Income Per Capita was $23,340 in 2006. The unemployment rate was 3.4% in December of 2015. This information suggests that Iowa's voters may not be as persuaded by Sanders' calls for economic reform, as they appear less directly impacted by recent economic downturn. On Industry/Campaign Finance:
Sanders' campaign has relied upon an influx of small donations, often $5- $100 in amount. This represents a shift from corporate influence on campaign finance, which has drawn support from individuals across party lines.
Clinton's campaign has received over $300,000,000 over the extent of her political career between 1999-2016. A majority of these donations are from individuals associated with major corporations. For example, Clinton's top donors between 1999-2016 are Citigroup, Goldman Sachs, DLA Piper, JP Morgan & Chase, and Morgan Stanley.
The Pivot Point:
Manufacturing represents 21% of the economy of Iowa. Insurance, Finance, and Banking also represent a large portion of the state's industry. Clinton's connections via campaign financing to these sectors and corporations may enable her to gain the upper-hand on this issue. Overall: 
While Bernie Sanders' message may resonate across the college campuses of American universities, it may not be the most ideal to resonate in the minds of the voters of Iowa. His campaign may be negatively impacted by its combative calls for regulation and taxation of the very industries that support the Iowan economy, and maintain the state's low unemployment rate. Meanwhile, recent shifts in Iowa's insurance market may endanger Clinton's campaign as the association is made between the effects of the Affordable Care Act and the growing monopolization of the insurance marketplace within the state.
